{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What a Language Model Does"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "language model (LM)"}, {"type": "text", "text": " assigns a probability to a sequence of tokens. Its core task is to estimate how likely the next token is, given all the tokens that came before it:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "P(w_1, w_2, \\ldots, w_T) = \\prod_{t=1}^{T} P(w_t \\mid w_1, \\ldots, w_{t-1})"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "This factorisation — called the "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "chain rule of probability"}, {"type": "text", "text": " — says that the joint probability of a sequence equals the product of conditional probabilities of each token given its history. A model that learns these conditionals well can "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "generate"}, {"type": "text", "text": " text by sampling one token at a time."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Training Objective"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Modern language models are trained with "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "next-token prediction"}, {"type": "text", "text": ". Given a document of T tokens, the model sees the first t-1 tokens and must predict token t — for every t in the document simultaneously. The loss is the average negative log-likelihood across all positions:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\mathcal{L} = -\\frac{1}{T} \\sum_{t=1}^{T} \\log P(w_t \\mid w_1, \\ldots, w_{t-1})"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "This is cross-entropy loss between the model's predicted distribution over the vocabulary and the one-hot true token. Minimising it forces the model to assign high probability to the actual next token."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Diagram showing next-token prediction: each prefix of 'The cat sat on the mat' becomes a training pair with the following token as the target"}}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Causal (Left-to-Right) Masking"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Because future tokens must not influence the prediction of the current token, transformer language models apply a "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "causal attention mask"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": position t can only attend to positions 1 through t. This makes training efficient — one forward pass over a sequence of T tokens produces T-1 training signal pairs — while ensuring the model learns a valid autoregressive distribution."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\n\ndef causal_mask(seq_len: int) -> torch.Tensor:\n    \"\"\"Returns upper-triangular mask; 0 = attend, -inf = block.\"\"\"\n    mask = torch.triu(torch.ones(seq_len, seq_len), diagonal=1)\n    return mask.masked_fill(mask == 1, float('-inf'))\n\nprint(causal_mask(4))\n# tensor([[  0., -inf, -inf, -inf],\n#         [  0.,   0., -inf, -inf],\n#         [  0.,   0.,   0., -inf],\n#         [  0.,   0.,   0.,   0.]])\n# Row i can attend to columns 0..i only."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Three Variants of the LM Objective"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Objective"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Direction"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Used by"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Best for"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Causal LM (CLM)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Left → right"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GPT family, LLaMA, Mistral"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Text generation, chat, completion"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Masked LM (MLM)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Bidirectional"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "BERT, RoBERTa"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Classification, NER, QA (not generation)"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Prefix LM / span"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Mixed"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "T5, UL2"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Seq2seq: translation, summarisation"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Causal LM is the dominant objective for modern large language models because the autoregressive property makes generation straightforward: sample a token, append it to context, repeat."}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Computing LM Loss in PyTorch"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\n# Vocabulary size V=5, sequence length T=4\nV, T = 5, 4\n\n# Model output: logits for each position (T, V)\nlogits = torch.tensor([\n    [2.0, 0.5, 0.1, 0.3, 0.1],  # position 1 predicts position 2\n    [0.1, 3.0, 0.2, 0.1, 0.1],  # position 2 predicts position 3\n    [0.2, 0.1, 0.1, 2.5, 0.1],  # position 3 predicts position 4\n    [0.1, 0.1, 0.1, 0.1, 3.0],  # position 4 predicts position 5 (if it existed)\n])\n\n# True next-token ids (the targets — shifted by one from inputs)\ntargets = torch.tensor([1, 2, 3, 4])  # token ids\n\n# Cross-entropy averages over positions automatically\nloss = F.cross_entropy(logits, targets)\nprint(f\"Loss: {loss.item():.4f}\")  # lower → model is more confident about correct tokens\n\n# In practice: logits come from model(input_ids), targets = input_ids[:, 1:]"}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "From Loss to Generation"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Once trained, the model converts logits to a probability distribution over the vocabulary with softmax and samples the next token. The choice of "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "decoding strategy"}, {"type": "text", "text": " controls the quality and diversity of the output:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Greedy"}, {"type": "text", "text": " — always pick the highest-probability token. Fast, deterministic, tends to be repetitive."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Sampling with temperature"}, {"type": "text", "text": " — divide logits by temperature T before softmax. T < 1 sharpens the distribution (more deterministic); T > 1 flattens it (more random)."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Top-k sampling"}, {"type": "text", "text": " — zero out all but the k most probable tokens, then sample. Prevents very low-probability tokens from ever being chosen."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Nucleus (top-p) sampling"}, {"type": "text", "text": " — keep the smallest set of tokens whose cumulative probability exceeds p. Adapts the candidate pool to the sharpness of the distribution."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Beam search"}, {"type": "text", "text": " — maintain B candidate sequences in parallel, keeping only the B highest-probability paths at each step. Better for tasks with a single correct answer (translation, code)."}]}]}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForCausalLM\nimport torch\n\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(\"gpt2\")\nmodel = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(\"gpt2\")\nmodel.eval()\n\nprompt = \"The language model objective is\"\ninput_ids = tokenizer(prompt, return_tensors=\"pt\").input_ids\n\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    # Greedy decoding\n    greedy = model.generate(input_ids, max_new_tokens=20)\n    # Sampling: temperature=0.9, top-p=0.95\n    sampled = model.generate(\n        input_ids,\n        do_sample=True,\n        temperature=0.9,\n        top_p=0.95,\n        max_new_tokens=20,\n    )\n\nprint(tokenizer.decode(greedy[0], skip_special_tokens=True))\nprint(tokenizer.decode(sampled[0], skip_special_tokens=True))"}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why This Objective Is Powerful"}]}, {"type": "blockquote", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Next-token prediction is a deceptively general objective. To predict the next word in a sentence about medicine, the model must implicitly learn medicine. To predict the next line in a code file, it must learn syntax and semantics. A sufficiently large model trained on a sufficiently large corpus develops broad capabilities as a side-effect of excelling at this one task — a property that explains the emergence of reasoning and instruction-following in large language models."}]}]}]}}